children.subject: Can we know when should we expect the announcement?
Should we expect the announcement to be made after the spring break? Or is there a possibility of knowing the decision during the spring break?
I honestly thought it was a typo at first as well. Do they recommend that?

They probably wanted to force mandatory p/np for everyone at first. However, there were quite a few opposing students, and they might have wanted to allow changes only for exceptional cases to calm the possible backlash. It's just my guessing, though. That is because when many students choose letter grade, some indirect disadvantages can be caused to students who need to be protected by the p/np policy.
Interesting... anyone care to share what action they will take? I'm not sure how to make this decision, especially regarding grad school admissions?

I don't think they're (Cal) gonna be out to get you if you change it to graded, it's just officially recommended against (if that's what you were asking about). Personally, I think grad schools will be sympathetic either way; if you take it graded then they will take that grade into account, but it probably won't reflect negatively on you at all if you do take everything P/NP because there's like, a global pandemic or something happening rn. Not sure if cherry picking would reflect slightly negatively if you choose easy classes only to take graded, but either way this is only one semester out of everything and all the other extra-academic things you will be showing grad schools, so I wouldn't overthink it too much. Do what's good for your mental health at this point.

Just don’t play with the grading policy, i.e., don’t choose to PNP some classes and letter grade the others. If you want letter grades to demonstrate your learning capability, then you should change all technical classes to letter grades, which is quite stressful and not recommended. Therefore, PNP all the classes is the recommended solution.

Serious question, in the grand scheme of things, how bad would cherry picking look though? Was considering it because I'm taking classes that I do want to contribute to my GPA, but having everything be graded would be too much and I don't want that. I didn't think it would be too big of a deal but also not sure.

I think if you cherry pick, grad schools will think you were on course for a lower grade in the courses you chose to P/NP. I'd highly recommend against it, unless some class is going to pull down your GPA significantly.
cherry picking will probably be viewed the same way that P/NPing a class in a normal semester would
I'm taking 61B, 188 and 127 this semester. Currently taking 61B for letter grade and PNPing 127. Will there be any difference if I letter grade/PNP 188?
From a grad school perspective, how would P/NPing R&C classes look, as compared to leaving your technical graded?

What are y'all's opinions on cherry-picking to boost GPA for resume purposes? I know most companies don't care much about GPA, but even so, I feel like i'm on the border of one of the traditional cutoffs that certain companies tend to have, and would like to cross it sooner rather than later. However, I'm kinda worried that P/NPing even one out of 3 techs (if I were to cherry-pick) might not look so good for certain other companies that ask for transcripts during the application process, and that P/NP-ing all 3 might look better, given the circumstances? Not sure, just wanted some peer-based opinions.

@Priyans Desai, if you're talking about stem grad programs, I don't think they consider whether you p/np GE or humanity requirements or not. Many people I know pn/p all their non-techs every single semester, that's really the purpose of p/np to start with.
@Anon Beaker 2 - the only company that asks for transcripts is Google, so you're safe everywhere else. I doubt Google cares if you PNP'd a course though, it's mostly interview performance...

I got roped into taking bio 1a for my bio breath but originally couldn't p/np it. For grad school do you think now p/nping Bio 1a and taking 189 and 188 for a grade will be fine or look bad since its a tech just not in the area or my desired focus? It's just a whole lot of memorization I can do without so I am leaning towards just passing out of it.

I just received an email from L+S and their last point (of 9) was "although we strongly recommend against it, students can request a letter grade provided they do so before May 8th." This is very shocking- does it mean that they recommend taking all courses P/NP?

Honestly, if you are sophomore or freshman, you shouldn’t worry this too much because you have plenty of opportunities to demonstrate your academic performance. What was said above is more for people who are taking several important upper divs together.
I feel like this is especially important for people who want to go to grad school in the area they're taking classes in this semester.
What about for sophomore/freshmen who are hoping to do undergrad CS research in the coming semesters? Would it be ideal to take the letter grade in CS classes?
@Anon Poet do keep in mind that there's plenty of people in 61A/61B/70 worried about the implications when it comes to declaring

I don't know if it eases your stress, but Prof. Sahai has been repeatedly saying in the CS 70 Piazza not to worry about this situation. He says that the EECS faculty is aware about the implications of a drastic decision towards declaring and they are working very hard to come up with a fair decision. He repeatedly emphasized the point to keep learning, rest assured.
Thank you Priyans :)

Does anyone else feel like having to decide p/np vs grading is actually stressful in itself? Seeing the above post it's making me think of things I didn't consider before i.e. grad schools thinking I'm on course for a lower grade by leaving one tech p/np and the other graded. I was on course for a good grade in one, but a mediocre grade in the other, does anyone feel the same type of stress about how our grades will be looked at? Because I don't want to be penalized for being on course for a good grade in one and a mediocre in the other and deciding to devote more of my time from now on to only one of them that matters for my GPA(61B). Does anyone have thoughts?

Would P/NPing affect grad school applications if the classes I'm taking this semester are upper divs? I'm a senior and taking 189 and 126. I read Professor Sahai's notes but saw that it applied mostly to lower divs. I'm leaning toward still taking these classes for a grade because I'm worried p/nping them will affect my grad school chances, even though it seems like the school is strongly recommending them to be taken p/np
How would p/np'ing one class and keeping the others graded if it was physics for example

history.content: The EECS department is currently updating our policy on P/NP grades due to the recent announcement from the Office of the Executive Vice Chancellor and Provost regarding the Spring 2020 semester. We will send an announcement to the community once we have a finalized plan. We understand these times are stressful and we appreciate your patience. Update: policy changes have been posted: @11574
